 You know, it's behavior is chaotic, right?

21:04.000 --> 21:07.960
 It's sort of, it's governed by these Hodgley,

21:07.960 --> 21:10.960
 Hawkskin equations in neuroscience, right?

21:10.960 --> 21:12.520
 Which are differential equations

21:12.520 --> 21:14.800
 that have a stochastic component, right?

21:14.800 --> 21:17.120
 Now, where does, you know, and this ultimately governs,

21:17.120 --> 21:19.680
 let's say, whether a neuron will fire or not fire, right?

21:19.680 --> 21:21.720
 So that's the basic chemical process

21:21.720 --> 21:23.880
 or electrical process by which signals

21:23.880 --> 21:24.800
 are sent in the brain.

21:24.800 --> 21:26.040
 Exactly, exactly.

21:26.040 --> 21:28.800
 And, you know, and so you could ask,

21:28.800 --> 21:31.400
 well, where does the randomness in the process,

21:31.400 --> 21:34.120
 you know, that neuroscientists,

21:34.120 --> 21:38.040
 or what neuroscientists would treat as randomness,

21:38.040 --> 21:39.400
 where does it come from?

21:39.400 --> 21:41.760
 You know, ultimately it's thermal noise, right?

21:41.760 --> 21:43.640
 Where does thermal noise come from?

21:43.640 --> 21:44.920
 Well, ultimately, you know,

21:44.920 --> 21:46.800
 there were some quantum mechanical events

21:46.800 --> 21:49.440
 at the molecular level that are getting sort of

21:49.440 --> 21:51.480
 chaotically amplified by, you know,

21:51.480 --> 21:53.720
 a sort of butterfly effect.

21:53.720 --> 21:57.280
 And so, you know, even if you knew

21:57.280 --> 22:00.600
 the complete quantum state of someone's brain, you know,

22:00.600 --> 22:02.840
 at best you could predict the probabilities

22:02.840 --> 22:05.480
 that they would do one thing or do another thing, right?

22:05.480 --> 22:06.800
 I think that part is actually

22:06.800 --> 22:09.080
 relatively uncontroversial, right?

22:09.080 --> 22:13.360
 The controversial question is whether any of it matters

22:13.360 --> 22:16.120
 for the sort of philosophical questions that we care about,

22:16.120 --> 22:18.360
 because you could say, if all it's doing

22:18.360 --> 22:20.360
 is just injecting some randomness

22:20.360 --> 22:23.720
 into an otherwise completely mechanistic process,

22:23.720 --> 22:25.160
 well, then who cares, right?

22:25.160 --> 22:28.480
 And more concretely, if you could build a machine

22:28.480 --> 22:30.680
 that, you know, could just calculate

22:30.680 --> 22:33.560
 the even just the probabilities

22:33.560 --> 22:36.000
 of all of the possible things that you would do, right?

22:36.000 --> 22:39.960
 And, you know, you know, of all the things that said

22:39.960 --> 22:41.880
 you had a 10% chance of doing,

22:41.880 --> 22:45.640
 you did exactly a 10th of them, you know, and so on and so on.

22:45.640 --> 22:47.360
 Yeah, that somehow also takes away

22:47.360 --> 22:48.200
 the feeling of free will.

22:48.200 --> 22:49.840
 Exactly, I mean, I mean, to me,

22:49.840 --> 22:51.880
 it seems essentially just as bad

22:51.880 --> 22:54.840
 as if the machine deterministically predicted you.

22:54.840 --> 22:57.360
 It seems, you know, hardly different from that.

22:57.360 --> 23:02.360
 So then, but a more subtle question is could you even learn

23:02.360 --> 23:06.360
 enough about someone's brain to do that, okay?

23:06.360 --> 23:09.520
 Because, you know, another central fact

23:09.520 --> 23:14.160
 about quantum mechanics is that making a measurement

23:14.160 --> 23:18.080
 on a quantum state is an inherently destructive operation.

23:18.080 --> 23:21.680
 Okay, so, you know, if I want to measure the, you know,

23:21.680 --> 23:23.480
 position of a particle, right?

23:23.480 --> 23:25.360
 It was, well, before I measured it,

23:25.360 --> 23:28.400
 it had a superposition over many different positions.

23:28.400 --> 23:31.000
 As soon as I measure, I localized it, right?

23:31.000 --> 23:32.360
 So now I know the position,

23:32.360 --> 23:35.240
 but I've also fundamentally changed the state.

23:35.240 --> 23:39.920
 And so you could say, well, maybe in trying to build

23:39.920 --> 23:42.800
 a model of someone's brain that was accurate enough

23:42.800 --> 23:44.720
 to actually, you know, make, let's say,

23:44.720 --> 23:48.360
 even well calibrated probabilistic predictions

23:48.360 --> 23:49.960
 of their future behavior,

23:49.960 --> 23:51.760
 maybe you would have to make measurements

23:51.760 --> 23:53.160
 that were just so accurate

23:53.160 --> 23:56.160
 that you would just fundamentally alter their brain, okay?

23:56.160 --> 23:59.560
 Or maybe not, maybe you only, you know,

23:59.560 --> 24:02.400
 it would suffice to just make some nano robots

24:02.400 --> 24:05.680
 that just measured some sort of much larger scale,

24:05.680 --> 24:08.760
 you know, macroscopic behavior, like, you know,

24:08.760 --> 24:10.760
 is, you know, what is this neuron doing?

24:10.760 --> 24:12.240
 What is that neuron doing?

24:12.240 --> 24:13.880
 Maybe that would be enough.

24:13.880 --> 24:16.960
 See, but now, you know, what I claim is that

24:16.960 --> 24:19.200
 we're now asking a question, you know,

24:19.200 --> 24:22.640
 in which, you know, it is possible to envision

24:22.640 --> 24:24.600
 what progress on it would look like.

24:24.600 --> 24:25.920
 Yeah, but just as you said,

24:25.920 --> 24:28.920
 that question may be slightly detached

24:28.920 --> 24:31.760
 from the philosophical question in the sense

24:31.760 --> 24:33.880
 if consciousness somehow has a role

24:33.880 --> 24:36.080
 to the experience of free will.

24:36.080 --> 24:38.400
 Because ultimately, when we're talking about free will,

24:38.400 --> 24:42.320
 we're also talking about not just the predictability

24:42.320 --> 24:44.920
 of our actions, but somehow the experience

24:44.920 --> 24:46.480
 of that predictability.

24:46.480 --> 24:49.440
 Yeah, well, I mean, a lot of philosophical questions,

24:49.440 --> 24:52.320
 ultimately, like feedback to the hard problem

24:52.320 --> 24:55.280
 of consciousness, you know, and as much as you can try

24:55.280 --> 24:57.200
 to sort of talk around it or not, right?

24:57.200 --> 24:59.960
 And, you know, and then there is a reason

24:59.960 --> 25:01.800
 why people try to talk around it,

25:01.800 --> 25:05.000
 which is that, you know, a Democratist

25:05.000 --> 25:07.760
 talked about the hard problem of consciousness,

25:07.760 --> 25:11.640
 you know, in 400 BC in terms that would be totally

25:11.640 --> 25:13.880
 recognizable to us today, right?

25:13.880 --> 25:16.960
 And it's really not clear if there's been progress since

25:16.960 --> 25:19.520
 or what progress could possibly consist of.

25:19.520 --> 25:22.440
 Is there a Q prime type of sub question

25:22.440 --> 25:24.400
 that could help us get at consciousness?

25:24.400 --> 25:25.680
 It's something about consciousness.

25:25.680 --> 25:27.760
 Well, I mean, well, I mean, there is the whole question

25:27.760 --> 25:29.640
 of, you know, of AI, right?

25:29.640 --> 25:33.720
 Of, you know, can you build a human level

25:33.720 --> 25:36.000
 or super human level AI?

25:36.000 --> 25:39.160
 And, you know, can it work in a completely different

25:39.160 --> 25:40.400
 substrate from the brain?

25:40.400 --> 25:43.480
 I mean, you know, and of course that was Alan Turing's point.

25:43.480 --> 25:45.520
 And, you know, and even if that was done,

25:45.520 --> 25:47.680
 it's, you know, maybe people would still argue

25:47.680 --> 25:49.960
 about the hard problem of consciousness, right?

