 for, you know, what a system could be doing

31:22.240 --> 31:25.920
 are described using numbers called amplitudes, okay,

31:25.920 --> 31:29.440
 which are like probabilities in some ways,

31:29.440 --> 31:31.200
 but they are not probabilities.

31:31.200 --> 31:32.840
 They can be positive, for one thing,

31:32.840 --> 31:34.920
 they can be positive or negative.

31:34.920 --> 31:37.520
 In fact, they can even be complex numbers.

31:37.520 --> 31:40.360
 Okay, and if you've heard of a quantum superposition,

31:40.360 --> 31:43.560
 this just means that some state of affairs

31:43.560 --> 31:45.760
 where you assign an amplitude,

31:45.760 --> 31:47.480
 one of these complex numbers,

31:47.480 --> 31:51.440
 to every possible configuration

31:51.440 --> 31:53.680
 that you could see a system in on measuring it.

31:53.680 --> 31:57.040
 So for example, you might say that an electron

31:57.040 --> 31:59.760
 has some amplitude for being here

31:59.760 --> 32:02.600
 and some other amplitude for being there, right?

32:02.600 --> 32:05.080
 Now, if you look to see where it is,

32:05.080 --> 32:06.800
 you will localize it, right?

32:06.800 --> 32:09.480
 You will sort of force the amplitudes

32:09.480 --> 32:12.560
 to be converted into probabilities.

32:12.560 --> 32:15.360
 That happens by taking their squared absolute value.

32:15.360 --> 32:19.840
 Okay, and then, you know, you can say

32:19.840 --> 32:22.960
 either the electron will be here or it will be there.

32:22.960 --> 32:24.560
 You know, knowing the amplitudes,

32:24.560 --> 32:26.920
 you can predict at least the probabilities

32:26.920 --> 32:30.240
 that you'll see each possible outcome, okay?

32:30.240 --> 32:32.880
 But while a system is isolated

32:32.880 --> 32:35.000
 from the whole rest of the universe,

32:35.000 --> 32:36.680
 the rest of its environment,

32:36.680 --> 32:39.160
 the amplitudes can change in time

32:39.160 --> 32:41.720
 by rules that are different

32:41.720 --> 32:44.760
 from the normal rules of probability

32:44.760 --> 32:47.840
 and that are, you know, alien to our everyday experience.

32:47.840 --> 32:50.680
 So anytime anyone ever tells you anything

32:50.680 --> 32:53.280
 about the weirdness of the quantum world, you know,

32:53.280 --> 32:56.240
 or assuming that they're not lying to you, right?

32:56.240 --> 32:58.000
 They are telling you, you know,

32:58.000 --> 33:00.440
 yet another consequence of nature

33:00.440 --> 33:03.360
 being described by these amplitudes.

33:03.360 --> 33:06.120
 So most famously, what amplitudes can do

33:06.120 --> 33:08.360
 is that they can interfere with each other, okay?

33:08.360 --> 33:11.560
 So in the famous double slit experiment,

33:11.560 --> 33:13.840
 what happens is that you shoot a particle,

33:13.840 --> 33:15.520
 like an electron, let's say,

33:15.520 --> 33:17.800
 at a screen with two slits in it,

33:17.800 --> 33:21.240
 and you find that they're, you know, on a second screen,

33:21.240 --> 33:22.920
 now there are certain places

33:22.920 --> 33:25.600
 where that electron will never end up, you know,

33:25.600 --> 33:29.640
 after it passes through the first screen.

33:29.640 --> 33:32.680
 And yet, if I close off one of the slits,

33:32.680 --> 33:35.560
 then the electron can appear in that place, okay?

33:35.560 --> 33:38.280
 So by decreasing the number of paths

33:38.280 --> 33:40.800
 that the electron could take to get somewhere,

33:40.800 --> 33:43.520
 you can increase the chance that it gets there, okay?

33:43.520 --> 33:45.400
 Now, how is that possible?

33:45.400 --> 33:48.840
 Well, it's because, you know, as we would say now,

33:48.840 --> 33:51.880
 the electron has a superposition state, okay?

33:51.880 --> 33:55.120
 It has some amplitude for reaching this point

33:55.120 --> 33:57.880
 by going through the first slit.

33:57.880 --> 33:59.960
 It has some other amplitude for reaching it

33:59.960 --> 34:01.800
 by going through the second slit.

34:01.800 --> 34:04.080
 But now if one amplitude is positive

34:04.080 --> 34:05.800
 and the other one is negative,

34:05.800 --> 34:08.160
 then I have to add them all up, right?

34:08.160 --> 34:10.880
 I have to add the amplitudes for every path

34:10.880 --> 34:13.880
 that the electron could have taken to reach this point.

34:13.880 --> 34:15.800
 And those amplitudes,

34:15.800 --> 34:17.920
 if they're pointing in different directions,

34:17.920 --> 34:19.840
 they can cancel each other out.

34:19.840 --> 34:22.200
 That would mean the total amplitude is zero,

34:22.200 --> 34:24.360
 and the thing never happens at all.

34:24.360 --> 34:26.480
 I close off one of the possibilities,

34:26.480 --> 34:28.960
 then the amplitude is positive or it's negative,

34:28.960 --> 34:30.600
 and now the thing can happen.

34:30.600 --> 34:34.200
 Okay, so that is sort of the one trick of quantum mechanics.

34:34.200 --> 34:37.200
 And now I can tell you what a quantum computer is, okay?

34:37.200 --> 34:41.360
 A quantum computer is a computer

34:41.360 --> 34:43.480
 that tries to exploit, you know,

34:43.480 --> 34:45.760
 these exactly these phenomena,

34:45.760 --> 34:49.240
 superposition, amplitudes and interference

34:49.240 --> 34:52.360
 in order to solve certain problems much faster

34:52.360 --> 34:54.560
 than we know how to solve them otherwise.

34:54.560 --> 34:57.040
 So it's the basic building block of a quantum computer

34:57.040 --> 35:00.240
 is what we call a quantum bit or a qubit.

35:00.240 --> 35:02.640
 That just means a bit that has some amplitude

35:02.640 --> 35:06.160
 for being zero and some other amplitude for being one.

35:06.160 --> 35:09.520
 So it's a superposition of zero and one states, right?

35:09.520 --> 35:12.600
 But now the key point is that if I've got,

35:12.600 --> 35:15.040
 let's say a thousand qubits,

35:15.040 --> 35:18.360
 the rules of quantum mechanics are completely unequivocal

35:18.360 --> 35:20.560
 that I do not just need one amplitude,

35:20.560 --> 35:22.880
 you know, I don't just need amplitudes for each qubit

35:22.880 --> 35:24.000
 separately, okay?

35:24.000 --> 35:28.480
 In general, I need an amplitude for every possible setting

35:28.480 --> 35:31.040
 of all thousand of those bits, okay?

35:31.040 --> 35:35.160
 So that what that means is two to the 1000 power amplitudes.

35:35.160 --> 35:37.880
 Okay, if I had to write those down,

35:37.880 --> 35:40.720
 let's say in the memory of a conventional computer,

35:40.720 --> 35:44.040
 if I had to write down two to the 1000 complex numbers,

35:44.040 --> 35:47.680
 that would not fit within the entire observable universe.

35:47.680 --> 35:51.160
 Okay, and yet, you know, quantum mechanics is unequivocal

35:51.160 --> 35:54.160
 that if these qubits can all interact with each other,

35:54.160 --> 35:58.320
 and in some sense, I need two to the 1000 parameters,

35:58.320 --> 36:01.480
 you know, amplitudes to describe what is going on.

36:01.480 --> 36:03.920
 Now, you know, now I can tell, you know,

36:03.920 --> 36:06.480
 where all the popular articles, you know,

36:06.480 --> 36:09.760
 about quantum computing go off the rails is that they say,

36:09.760 --> 36:12.240
 you know, they sort of say what I just said,

36:12.240 --> 36:14.960
 then they say, oh, so the way a quantum computer works

36:14.960 --> 36:18.200
 is just by trying every possible answer in parallel.

36:18.200 --> 36:21.360
 So, you know, that sounds too good to be true.

36:21.360 --> 36:24.960
 And unfortunately, it kind of is too good to be true.

36:24.960 --> 36:28.320
 The problem is I could make a superposition

36:28.320 --> 36:31.600
 over every possible answer to my problem, you know,

36:31.600 --> 36:34.320
 even if there are two to the 1000 of them, right?

36:34.320 --> 36:36.120
 I can easily do that.

36:36.120 --> 36:38.520
 The trouble is for a computer to be useful,

36:38.520 --> 36:40.640
 you've got, at some point, you've got to look at it

36:40.640 --> 36:42.720
 and see an output, right?

36:42.720 --> 36:45.040
 And if I just measure a superposition

36:45.040 --> 36:47.080
 over every possible answer,

36:47.080 --> 36:49.000
 then the rules of quantum mechanics tell me

36:49.000 --> 36:51.680
 that all I'll see will be a random answer.

36:51.680 --> 36:53.360
 You know, if I just wanted a random answer,

36:53.360 --> 36:54.800
 well, I could have picked one myself

36:54.800 --> 36:56.640
 with a lot less trouble, right?

36:56.640 --> 37:00.280
 So the entire trick with quantum computing,

37:00.280 --> 37:03.000
 with every algorithm for a quantum computer,

37:03.000 --> 37:06.000
 is that you try to choreograph a pattern

37:06.000 --> 37:08.600
 of interference of amplitudes.

37:08.600 --> 37:11.680
 And you try to do it so that for each wrong answer,

37:11.680 --> 37:14.280
 some of the paths leading to that wrong answer

37:14.280 --> 37:18.120
 have positive amplitudes and others have negative amplitudes.

37:18.120 --> 37:20.760
 So on the whole, they cancel each other out, okay?

37:20.760 --> 37:23.600
 Whereas all the paths leading to the right answer

37:23.600 --> 37:25.800
 should reinforce each other, you know,

37:25.800 --> 37:28.240
 should have amplitudes pointing the same direction.

37:28.240 --> 37:30.800
 So the design of algorithms in this space

37:30.800 --> 37:33.280
 is the choreography of the interferences.

37:33.280 --> 37:35.280
 Precisely, that's precisely what it is.

37:35.280 --> 37:39.960
 Can we take a brief step back and you mentioned information.

37:39.960 --> 37:40.800
 Yes.

37:40.800 --> 37:43.360
 So in which part of this beautiful picture

37:43.360 --> 37:46.800
 that you've painted is information contained?

37:46.800 --> 37:49.000
 Oh, well, information is at the core

37:49.000 --> 37:51.160
 of everything that we've been talking about, right?

37:51.160 --> 37:53.120
 I mean, the bit is, you know,

37:53.120 --> 37:55.440
 the basic unit of information,

37:55.440 --> 37:59.120
 since, you know, Colad Shannon's paper in 1948.

37:59.120 --> 38:00.120
 You know, and, you know, of course,

38:00.120 --> 38:02.360
 you know, people had the concept even before that.

38:02.360 --> 38:05.320
 You know, he popularized the name, right?

38:05.320 --> 38:06.160
 But I mean.

38:06.160 --> 38:07.920
 But a bit is zero or one.

38:07.920 --> 38:08.760
 That's right.

38:08.760 --> 38:09.600
 So that's the basic answer.

38:09.600 --> 38:11.880
 And what we would say is that the basic unit

38:11.880 --> 38:14.680
 of quantum information is the qubit,

38:14.680 --> 38:17.120
 is, you know, the object, any object

38:17.120 --> 38:21.000
 that can be maintained and manipulated

38:21.000 --> 38:24.160
 in a superposition of zero and one states.

38:24.160 --> 38:26.160
 Now, you know, sometimes people ask,

38:26.160 --> 38:29.160
 well, but what is a qubit physically, right?

38:29.160 --> 38:32.400
 And there are all these different, you know,

38:32.400 --> 38:34.840
 proposals that are being pursued in parallel

38:34.840 --> 38:37.040
 for how you implement qubits.

38:37.040 --> 38:39.800
 There is, you know, superconducting quantum computing

38:39.800 --> 38:41.560
 that was in the news recently

38:41.560 --> 38:45.080
 because of Google's quantum supremacy experiment, right?

38:45.080 --> 38:49.600
 Where you would have some little coils

38:49.600 --> 38:52.360
 where a current can flow through them

38:52.360 --> 38:54.440
 in two different energy states.

38:54.440 --> 38:57.680
 One representing a zero, another representing a one.

38:57.680 --> 38:59.360
 And if you cool these coils

38:59.360 --> 39:02.320
 to just slightly above absolute zero,

39:02.320 --> 39:05.600
 like a hundredth of a degree, then they superconduct.

39:05.600 --> 39:07.440
 And then the current can actually be

39:07.440 --> 39:10.760
 in a superposition of the two different states.

39:10.760 --> 39:12.440
 So that's one kind of qubit.

39:12.440 --> 39:14.600
 Another kind would be, you know,

39:14.600 --> 39:17.840
 just an individual atomic nucleus, right?

39:17.840 --> 39:19.080
 It has a spin.

39:19.080 --> 39:21.160
 It could be spinning clockwise.

39:21.160 --> 39:23.240
 It could be spinning counterclockwise.

39:23.240 --> 39:26.120
 Or it could be in a superposition of the two spin states.

39:26.120 --> 39:27.680
 That is another qubit.

39:27.680 --> 39:30.360
 But so just like in the classical world, right?

39:30.360 --> 39:32.920
 You could be a virtuoso programmer

39:32.920 --> 39:36.480
 without having any idea of what a transistor is, right?

39:36.480 --> 39:39.080
 Or how the bits are physically represented

39:39.080 --> 39:40.440
 inside the machine,

39:40.440 --> 39:43.320
 even that the machine uses electricity, right?

39:43.320 --> 39:45.080
 You just care about the logic.

39:45.080 --> 39:47.320
 It's sort of the same with quantum computing, right?

39:47.320 --> 39:49.000
 Cubits could be realized

39:49.000 --> 39:51.440
 by many, many different quantum systems.

39:51.440 --> 39:54.520
 And yet all of those systems will lead to the same logic,

39:54.520 --> 39:58.680
 you know, the logic of qubits and how, you know,

39:58.680 --> 40:01.560
 how you measure them, how you change them over time.

40:01.560 --> 40:04.040
 And so, you know, the subject of, you know,

40:04.040 --> 40:07.520
 how qubits behave and what you can do with qubits,

40:07.520 --> 40:09.320
 that is quantum information.

40:09.320 --> 40:11.000
 So just to linger on that.

40:11.000 --> 40:11.840
 Sure.

40:11.840 --> 40:14.640
 So the physical design implementation of a qubit

40:15.600 --> 40:20.600
 does not interfere with that next level of abstraction

40:20.880 --> 40:22.520
 that you can program over it.

40:22.520 --> 40:27.120
 So it truly is, the idea of it is, is it okay?

40:27.120 --> 40:28.840
 Well, to be honest with you,

40:28.840 --> 40:30.840
 today they do interfere with each other.

40:30.840 --> 40:33.880
 That's because all the quantum computers we can build today

40:33.880 --> 40:35.480
 are very noisy, right?

40:35.480 --> 40:37.920
 And so sort of the, you know,

40:37.920 --> 40:41.040
 the qubits are very far from perfect.

40:41.040 --> 40:44.080
 And so the lower level sort of does affect the higher levels

40:44.080 --> 40:46.640
 and we sort of have to think about all of them at once.

40:46.640 --> 40:49.320
 Okay, but eventually where we hope to get

40:49.320 --> 40:52.640
 is to what are called error corrected quantum computers

40:52.640 --> 40:54.680
 where the qubits really do behave

40:54.680 --> 40:58.920
 like perfect abstract qubits for as long as we want them to.

40:58.920 --> 41:01.680
 And in that future, you know, the, you know,

41:01.680 --> 41:05.080
 a future that we can already sort of prove theorems about

41:05.080 --> 41:08.440
 or think about today, but in that future,

41:08.440 --> 41:11.280
 the logic of it really does become decoupled

41:11.280 --> 41:12.120
 from the hardware.

41:12.120 --> 41:16.360
 So if noise is currently like the biggest problem

41:16.360 --> 41:18.360
 for quantum computing,

41:18.360 --> 41:23.160
 and then the dream is error correcting quantum computers,

41:23.160 --> 41:26.760
 can you just maybe describe what does it mean

41:26.760 --> 41:28.880
 for there to be noise in the system?

41:28.880 --> 41:29.840
 Absolutely.

41:29.840 --> 41:32.680
 So yeah, so the problem is even a little more specific

41:32.680 --> 41:35.400
 than noise, so that the fundamental problem,

41:35.400 --> 41:38.480
 if you're trying to actually build a quantum computer,

41:38.480 --> 41:41.320
 you know, of any appreciable size

41:41.320 --> 41:43.840
 is something called decoherence.

41:43.840 --> 41:46.400
 Okay, and this was recognized from the very beginning,

41:46.400 --> 41:48.600
 you know, when people first started thinking about this

41:48.600 --> 41:50.080
 in the 1990s.

41:50.080 --> 41:54.040
 Now, what decoherence means is sort of the unwanted

41:54.040 --> 41:57.280
 interaction between, you know, your qubits, you know,

41:57.280 --> 41:59.360
 the state of your quantum computer

41:59.360 --> 42:01.240
 and the external environment.

42:01.240 --> 42:03.240
 Okay, and why is that such a problem?

42:03.240 --> 42:05.360
 Well, I talked before about how, you know,

42:05.360 --> 42:07.840
 when you measure a quantum system,

42:07.840 --> 42:11.200
 so let's say if I measure a qubit that's in a superposition

42:11.200 --> 42:13.160
 of zero and one states to ask it, you know,

42:13.160 --> 42:14.880
 are you zero or are you one?

42:14.880 --> 42:17.240
 Well, now I force it to make up its mind, right?

42:17.240 --> 42:21.000
 And now, probabilistically, it chooses one or the other.

42:21.000 --> 42:23.480
 And now, you know, it's no longer a superposition,

42:23.480 --> 42:25.240
 there's no longer amplitudes.

42:25.240 --> 42:27.720
 There's just, there's some probability that I get a zero

42:27.720 --> 42:29.320
 and there's some that I get a one.

42:30.320 --> 42:35.400
 And now, the trouble is that it doesn't have to be me

42:35.400 --> 42:36.240
 who's looking.

42:36.240 --> 42:39.240
 Okay, or in fact, it doesn't have to be any conscious entity.

42:40.480 --> 42:44.360
 Any kind of interaction with the external world

42:44.360 --> 42:48.360
 that leaks out the information about whether this qubit

42:48.360 --> 42:52.560
 was a zero or a one, sort of that causes the zeroness

42:52.560 --> 42:56.360
 or the oneness of the qubit to be recorded in, you know,

42:56.360 --> 43:00.600
 the radiation in the room, in the molecules of the air,

43:00.600 --> 43:04.920
 in the wires that are connected to my device, any of that.

43:06.080 --> 43:08.160
 As soon as the information leaks out,

43:08.160 --> 43:11.160
 it is as if that qubit has been measured, okay?

43:11.160 --> 43:15.280
 It is, you know, the state has now collapsed.

43:15.280 --> 43:17.800
 You know, another way to say it is that it's become entangled

43:17.800 --> 43:19.480
 with its environment, okay?

43:19.480 --> 43:21.960
 But, you know, from the perspective of someone

43:21.960 --> 43:23.600
 who's just looking at this qubit,

43:23.600 --> 43:26.880
 it is as though it has lost its quantum state.

43:26.880 --> 43:29.880
 And so what this means is that if I want to do

43:29.880 --> 43:33.680
 a quantum computation, I have to keep the qubits

43:33.680 --> 43:37.600
 sort of fanatically well isolated from their environment.

43:37.600 --> 43:40.480
 But then at the same time, they can't be perfectly isolated

43:40.480 --> 43:42.680
 because I need to tell them what to do.

43:42.680 --> 43:45.960
 I need to make them interact with each other for one thing.

43:45.960 --> 43:49.840
 And not only that, but in a precisely choreographed way.

43:49.840 --> 43:53.520
 Okay, and, you know, that is such a staggering problem, right?

43:53.520 --> 43:56.440
 How do I isolate these qubits from the whole universe,

43:56.440 --> 43:58.880
 but then also tell them exactly what to do?

43:58.880 --> 44:01.520
 I mean, you know, there were distinguished physicists

44:01.520 --> 44:04.360
 and computer scientists in the 90s

44:04.360 --> 44:07.160
 who said this is fundamentally impossible, you know?

44:07.160 --> 44:10.680
 The laws of physics will just never let you control qubits

44:10.680 --> 44:14.240
 to the degree of accuracy that you're talking about.

44:14.240 --> 44:17.680
 Now, what changed the views of most of us

44:17.680 --> 44:22.280
 was a profound discovery in the mid to late 90s,

44:22.280 --> 44:25.440
 which was called the theory of quantum error correction

44:25.440 --> 44:27.400
 and quantum fault tolerance.

44:27.400 --> 44:29.760
 Okay, and the upshot of that theory

44:29.760 --> 44:33.560
 is that if I want to build a reliable quantum computer

44:33.560 --> 44:36.480
 and scale it up to, you know, an arbitrary number

44:36.480 --> 44:38.680
 of as many qubits as I want, you know,

44:38.680 --> 44:41.280
 and doing as much on them as I want,

44:41.280 --> 44:43.600
 I do not actually have to get the qubits

44:43.600 --> 44:46.160
 perfectly isolated from their environment.

44:46.160 --> 44:49.720
 It is enough to get them really, really, really well isolated.

44:49.720 --> 44:54.720
 Okay, and even if every qubit is sort of leaking,

44:54.720 --> 44:57.920
 you know, its state into the environment at some rate,

44:57.920 --> 45:00.280
 as long as that rate is low enough,

45:00.280 --> 45:03.680
 okay, I can sort of encode the information

45:03.680 --> 45:06.720
 that I care about in very clever ways

45:06.720 --> 45:10.040
 across the collective states of multiple qubits.

45:10.040 --> 45:12.480
 Okay, in such a way that even if, you know,

45:12.480 --> 45:15.120
 a small percentage of my qubits leak,

45:15.120 --> 45:17.000
 well, I'm constantly monitoring them

45:17.000 --> 45:18.520
 to see if that leak happened.

45:18.520 --> 45:21.080
 I can detect it and I can correct it.

45:21.080 --> 45:23.440
 I can recover the information I care about

45:23.440 --> 45:25.520
 from the remaining qubits, okay?

45:25.520 --> 45:30.360
 And so, you know, you can build a reliable quantum computer

45:30.360 --> 45:32.840
 even out of unreliable parts, right?

45:32.840 --> 45:35.840
 Now the, in some sense, you know,

45:35.840 --> 45:39.160
 that discovery is what set the engineering agenda

45:39.160 --> 45:41.120
 for quantum computing research

45:41.120 --> 45:43.760
 from the 1990s until the present, okay?

45:43.760 --> 45:46.760
 The goal has been, you know, engineer qubits

45:46.760 --> 45:49.080
 that are not perfectly reliable,

45:49.080 --> 45:52.000
 but reliable enough that you can then use

45:52.000 --> 45:56.280
 these error correcting codes to have them simulate qubits

45:56.280 --> 45:59.120
 that are even more reliable than they are, right?

45:59.120 --> 46:01.120
 The error correction becomes a net win

46:01.120 --> 46:02.960
 rather than a net loss, right?

46:02.960 --> 46:05.960
 And then once you reach that sort of crossover point,

46:05.960 --> 46:09.120
 then, you know, your simulated qubits could in turn

46:09.120 --> 46:11.640
 simulate qubits that are even more reliable

46:11.640 --> 46:13.760
 and so on until you've just, you know,

46:13.760 --> 46:17.160
 effectively you have arbitrarily reliable qubits.

46:17.160 --> 46:20.840
 So long story short, we are not at that break even point yet.

46:20.840 --> 46:22.720
 We're a hell of a lot closer than we were

46:22.720 --> 46:24.840
 when people started doing this in the 90s,

46:24.840 --> 46:26.480
 like orders of magnitude closer.

46:26.480 --> 46:30.160
 But the key ingredient there is the more qubits, the better.

46:30.160 --> 46:31.120
 Because...

46:31.120 --> 46:32.240
 Well, the more qubits,

